<subSubSection id="5FC46559FFF32E3CFF3A25337514F83C" pageId="13" pageNumber="214" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="176136D2FFF32E3CFF3A25337514F83C" blockId="13.[151,1436,1817,2022]" pageId="13" pageNumber="214">
<emphasis id="25AAEAC0FFF32E3CFF3A2533765DF8CF" bold="true" box="[199,321,1817,1842]" pageId="13" pageNumber="214">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="D0DE4D51FFF32E3CFEB22533750BF8CF" box="[335,535,1817,1842]" class="Insecta" family="Lecithoceridae" genus="Ptilothyris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="214" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pilosa">
<emphasis id="25AAEAC0FFF32E3CFEB22533750BF8CF" box="[335,535,1817,1842]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="214">Ptilothyris pilosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is hardly distinguishable from 
<taxonomicName id="D0DE4D51FFF32E3CFC6A2530738BF8CF" authority="Meyrick" authorityName="Meyr., E. Meyrick" authorityYear="1932" box="[919,1175,1817,1842]" class="Insecta" family="Lecithoceridae" genus="Ptilothyris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="214" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="serangota">
<emphasis id="25AAEAC0FFF32E3CFC6A25307336F8CC" box="[919,1066,1818,1841]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="214">P. serangota</emphasis>
Meyrick
</taxonomicName>
with their superficial characters, but it can be distinguished by the male genitalia: ventral plate of juxta with nearly similar size, short caudal lobes, never with such a long and pointed process as in 
<taxonomicName id="D0DE4D51FFF32E3CFCAE254874C2F884" authorityName="Meyr., E. Meyrick" authorityYear="1932" box="[851,990,1890,1913]" class="Insecta" family="Lecithoceridae" genus="Ptilothyris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="214" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="serangota">
<emphasis id="25AAEAC0FFF32E3CFCAE254874C2F884" box="[851,990,1890,1913]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="214">P. serangota</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; phallus shorter and thicker than that of 
<taxonomicName id="D0DE4D51FFF32E3CFF6A25AC763EF860" authorityName="Meyr., E. Meyrick" authorityYear="1932" box="[151,290,1926,1949]" class="Insecta" family="Lecithoceridae" genus="Ptilothyris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="214" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="serangota">
<emphasis id="25AAEAC0FFF32E3CFF6A25AC763EF860" box="[151,290,1926,1949]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="214">P. serangota</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; cornutus thin, angled near middle, curved upward basally and downward apically, claw-like apically, but not observed in 
<taxonomicName id="D0DE4D51FFF32E3CFE882580751DF83C" authorityName="Meyr., E. Meyrick" authorityYear="1932" box="[373,513,1962,1985]" class="Insecta" family="Lecithoceridae" genus="Ptilothyris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="214" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="serangota">
<emphasis id="25AAEAC0FFF32E3CFE882580751DF83C" box="[373,513,1962,1985]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="214">P. serangota</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="5FC46559FFF32E3FFF3A25E77679FB4C" lastPageId="14" lastPageNumber="215" pageId="13" pageNumber="214" type="description">
<paragraph id="176136D2FFF32E3CFF3A25E7733CF818" blockId="13.[151,1436,1817,2022]" box="[199,1056,1997,2022]" pageId="13" pageNumber="214">
<emphasis id="25AAEAC0FFF32E3CFF3A25E77645F81B" bold="true" box="[199,345,1997,2022]" pageId="13" pageNumber="214">Description.</emphasis>
Male and female (
<figureCitation id="8FE52A57FFF32E3CFDD725E7756AF81B" box="[554,630,1997,2022]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="13.[151,250,1658,1680]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,209,1621]" captionTargetId="figure@13.[151,1435,193,1637]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURE 8. Ptilothyris pilosa Park. A, Holotype, male, in MfN; B, Female from Uganda; C, Antenna, holotype; D, Venation, paratype, wing slide CIS-7118; E, Male genitalia, holotype, gen. slide no. CIS-7075; F, Phallus; G, Lateral view of male genitalia; H, Juxta, paratype, gen. slide no. CIS-7002 (specimen same as 8D); I, Juxta, paratype, gen. slide no. CIS-7069; J, Abdomen, with hair-pencils, holotype." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2594875/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="214">Figs. 8</figureCitation>
A–D). Forewing length 9.5–11.0 mm.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="176136D2FFF02E3FFF3A22BD7232FE99" blockId="14.[151,1437,151,1273]" pageId="14" pageNumber="215">
<emphasis id="25AAEAC0FFF02E3FFF3A22BD7618FF4D" box="[199,260,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="215">Head</emphasis>
: Dark purple dorsally, with light orange scales laterally, arising from upper margin of compound eye. Antenna sexually dimorphic; in male (
<figureCitation id="8FE52A57FFF02E3FFDA3229675A6FF29" box="[606,698,188,213]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="13.[151,250,1658,1680]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,209,1621]" captionTargetId="figure@13.[151,1435,193,1637]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURE 8. Ptilothyris pilosa Park. A, Holotype, male, in MfN; B, Female from Uganda; C, Antenna, holotype; D, Venation, paratype, wing slide CIS-7118; E, Male genitalia, holotype, gen. slide no. CIS-7075; F, Phallus; G, Lateral view of male genitalia; H, Juxta, paratype, gen. slide no. CIS-7002 (specimen same as 8D); I, Juxta, paratype, gen. slide no. CIS-7069; J, Abdomen, with hair-pencils, holotype." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2594875/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="215">Fig. 8C</figureCitation>
), basal segment slender, dark purple dorsally and light orange ventrally; flagellum strongly bipectinate with long flagellomeral branches, dark purple in basal 3/5, then orange white beyond, with gradually shortened flagellomeral branches; in female, slender, slightly serrated (
<figureCitation id="8FE52A57FFF02E3FFACF232E7292FEE1" box="[1330,1422,260,285]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="13.[151,250,1658,1680]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,209,1621]" captionTargetId="figure@13.[151,1435,193,1637]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURE 8. Ptilothyris pilosa Park. A, Holotype, male, in MfN; B, Female from Uganda; C, Antenna, holotype; D, Venation, paratype, wing slide CIS-7118; E, Male genitalia, holotype, gen. slide no. CIS-7075; F, Phallus; G, Lateral view of male genitalia; H, Juxta, paratype, gen. slide no. CIS-7002 (specimen same as 8D); I, Juxta, paratype, gen. slide no. CIS-7069; J, Abdomen, with hair-pencils, holotype." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2594875/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="215">Fig. 8B</figureCitation>
). Labial palpus, rather flattened, saber-shaped, light orange all around; second segment thickened; 3rd segment slender, as long as 2nd segment, densely speckling with black scales ventrally, with acute, blackish apex.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="176136D2FFF02E3FFF3A234573D5FD25" blockId="14.[151,1437,151,1273]" pageId="14" pageNumber="215">
<emphasis id="25AAEAC0FFF02E3FFF3A23457604FE75" box="[199,280,367,392]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="215">Thorax</emphasis>
: Notum and tegula dark purple. Hind tibia with light orange dorsally and black scales on outer surface in basal 2/5, then pale orange in median 1/5, and with black scales all around in distal 2/5, with light orange apex; first tarsus black with light orange apex. Forewing elongate, ground color dark purple; antemedian fascia broad, well-developed in basal 2/5; postmedian fascia narrow, strongly convex outwardly at middle; costa slightly convex in basal 1/4, slightly concave medially, distinctly convex from 3/4, then oblique; apex obtuse; termen slightly oblique; cell closed; venation (
<figureCitation id="8FE52A57FFF02E3FFE02200E7546FDC1" box="[511,602,548,573]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="13.[151,250,1658,1680]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,209,1621]" captionTargetId="figure@13.[151,1435,193,1637]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURE 8. Ptilothyris pilosa Park. A, Holotype, male, in MfN; B, Female from Uganda; C, Antenna, holotype; D, Venation, paratype, wing slide CIS-7118; E, Male genitalia, holotype, gen. slide no. CIS-7075; F, Phallus; G, Lateral view of male genitalia; H, Juxta, paratype, gen. slide no. CIS-7002 (specimen same as 8D); I, Juxta, paratype, gen. slide no. CIS-7069; J, Abdomen, with hair-pencils, holotype." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2594875/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="215">Fig. 8D</figureCitation>
) with R 
<subScript id="8B5A3497FFF02E3FFD41201875D8FDBD" attach="left" box="[700,708,562,576]" fontSize="6" pageId="14" pageNumber="215">5</subScript>
arising before middle, bent anteriorly at near base; R 
<subScript id="8B5A3497FFF02E3FFAC120187258FDBD" attach="left" box="[1340,1348,562,576]" fontSize="6" pageId="14" pageNumber="215">3</subScript>
and R 
<subScript id="8B5A3497FFF02E3FFA6920187280FDBD" attach="left" box="[1428,1436,562,576]" fontSize="6" pageId="14" pageNumber="215">4</subScript>
stalked for near basal 1/3; R 
<subScript id="8B5A3497FFF02E3FFE2B207376C2FD9A" attach="left" box="[470,478,601,615]" fontSize="6" pageId="14" pageNumber="215">4</subScript>
reaching before apex; R 
<subScript id="8B5A3497FFF02E3FFD08207375E1FD9A" attach="left" box="[757,765,601,615]" fontSize="6" pageId="14" pageNumber="215">5</subScript>
absent
<subScript id="8B5A3497FFF02E3FFCB12073744CFD9A" attach="left" box="[844,848,601,615]" fontSize="6" pageId="14" pageNumber="215">;</subScript>
M 
<subScript id="8B5A3497FFF02E3FFC9020737469FD9A" attach="left" box="[877,885,601,615]" fontSize="6" pageId="14" pageNumber="215">1</subScript>
remote from R 
<subScript id="8B5A3497FFF02E3FFBD920737320FD9A" attach="left" box="[1060,1084,601,615]" fontSize="6" pageId="14" pageNumber="215">3+4</subScript>
at base; M 
<subScript id="8B5A3497FFF02E3FFB47207373DEFD9A" attach="left" box="[1210,1218,601,615]" fontSize="6" pageId="14" pageNumber="215">2</subScript>
arising from lower corner of cell; M 
<subScript id="8B5A3497FFF02E3FFEA920AA7640FD73" attach="left" box="[340,348,640,654]" fontSize="6" pageId="14" pageNumber="215">3</subScript>
, CuA 
<subScript id="8B5A3497FFF02E3FFE6320AA76BAFD73" attach="left" box="[414,422,640,654]" fontSize="6" pageId="14" pageNumber="215">1</subScript>
and CuA 
<subScript id="8B5A3497FFF02E3FFDEF20AA7506FD73" attach="left" box="[530,538,640,654]" fontSize="6" pageId="14" pageNumber="215">2</subScript>
on common stalk; distance between M 
<subScript id="8B5A3497FFF02E3FFC2D20AA74C4FD73" attach="left" box="[976,984,640,654]" fontSize="6" pageId="14" pageNumber="215">3</subScript>
and CuA 
<subScript id="8B5A3497FFF02E3FFBBE20AA7357FD73" attach="left" box="[1091,1099,640,654]" fontSize="6" pageId="14" pageNumber="215">1</subScript>
at base nearly equal to that of CuA 
<subScript id="8B5A3497FFF02E3FFF31208C77C8FD49" attach="left" box="[204,212,678,692]" fontSize="6" pageId="14" pageNumber="215">1</subScript>
and CuA 
<subScript id="8B5A3497FFF02E3FFEBB208C7652FD49" attach="left" box="[326,334,678,692]" fontSize="6" pageId="14" pageNumber="215">2</subScript>
at base. Hind wing broader than forewing; ground color same as that of forewing, with white hyaline patch, extending to the end of cell; venation with M 
<subScript id="8B5A3497FFF02E3FFCC920E77420FD26" attach="left" box="[820,828,717,731]" fontSize="6" pageId="14" pageNumber="215">2</subScript>
absent; M 
<subScript id="8B5A3497FFF02E3FFC4F20E774A6FD26" attach="left" box="[946,954,717,731]" fontSize="6" pageId="14" pageNumber="215">3</subScript>
and CuA 
<subScript id="8B5A3497FFF02E3FFBDF20E77336FD26" attach="left" box="[1058,1066,717,731]" fontSize="6" pageId="14" pageNumber="215">1</subScript>
short-stalked.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="176136D2FFF02E3FFF3A20C27689FCB5" blockId="14.[151,1437,151,1273]" pageId="14" pageNumber="215">
<emphasis id="25AAEAC0FFF02E3FFF3A20C2762DFCFC" box="[199,305,744,769]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="215">Abdomen</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="8FE52A57FFF02E3FFEBC20C2768FFCFC" box="[321,403,744,769]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="13.[151,250,1658,1680]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,209,1621]" captionTargetId="figure@13.[151,1435,193,1637]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURE 8. Ptilothyris pilosa Park. A, Holotype, male, in MfN; B, Female from Uganda; C, Antenna, holotype; D, Venation, paratype, wing slide CIS-7118; E, Male genitalia, holotype, gen. slide no. CIS-7075; F, Phallus; G, Lateral view of male genitalia; H, Juxta, paratype, gen. slide no. CIS-7002 (specimen same as 8D); I, Juxta, paratype, gen. slide no. CIS-7069; J, Abdomen, with hair-pencils, holotype." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2594875/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="215">Fig. 8J</figureCitation>
): Ventral surface pale orange from 1 
<superScript id="E0AB9B9AFFF02E3FFCCF20CF7420FD0E" attach="left" box="[818,828,741,755]" fontSize="6" pageId="14" pageNumber="215">st</superScript>
to 4 
<superScript id="E0AB9B9AFFF02E3FFC8D20CF7460FD0E" attach="left" box="[880,892,741,755]" fontSize="6" pageId="14" pageNumber="215">th</superScript>
segment, then fuscous beyond, densely spinous on tergites, with a pair of long hair-pencils on anterior margin of segment VIII; the hair-pencil twice longer than the length of segment VII.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="176136D2FFF02E3FFF3A217E7679FB4C" blockId="14.[151,1437,151,1273]" pageId="14" pageNumber="215">
Male genitalia (
<figureCitation id="8FE52A57FFF02E3FFE7D217E76CCFC90" box="[384,464,852,877]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="13.[151,250,1658,1680]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,209,1621]" captionTargetId="figure@13.[151,1435,193,1637]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURE 8. Ptilothyris pilosa Park. A, Holotype, male, in MfN; B, Female from Uganda; C, Antenna, holotype; D, Venation, paratype, wing slide CIS-7118; E, Male genitalia, holotype, gen. slide no. CIS-7075; F, Phallus; G, Lateral view of male genitalia; H, Juxta, paratype, gen. slide no. CIS-7002 (specimen same as 8D); I, Juxta, paratype, gen. slide no. CIS-7069; J, Abdomen, with hair-pencils, holotype." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2594875/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="215">Figs. 8</figureCitation>
E–I) with uncus broadened distally, fan-shaped, emarginated mesially along caudal margin. Basal plate of gnathos large, as wide as uncus, trifurcated caudally, with long median lobe rounded apically, exceeding apices of lateral lobes; median process extremely broad at base, curved downward subapically. Valva elongate, with nearly parallel sides before cucullus; costa slightly convex near base, concave medially; cucullus elongate, more or less triangular with long hairs around ventro-proximal margin, apex obtuse. Juxta bifurcate, with different length of caudal lobes ventrally: left lobe shorter, slightly acute apically, right one rounded apically, slightly bigger than the left; dorsal plate very shortened, with triangular processes laterally. Vinculum a band, narrow, well sclerotized. Phallus rather slender, slightly arched, narrowed toward apex, slightly shorter than valva; cornutus small, heavily sclerotized, angled near middle, curved upward basally and downward apically, claw-like apically.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="5FC46559FFF02E3FFF3A269676DAFB28" box="[199,454,1212,1237]" pageId="14" pageNumber="215" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="176136D2FFF02E3FFF3A269676DAFB28" blockId="14.[151,1437,151,1273]" box="[199,454,1212,1237]" pageId="14" pageNumber="215">
<emphasis id="25AAEAC0FFF02E3FFF3A2696767CFB28" bold="true" box="[199,352,1212,1237]" pageId="14" pageNumber="215">Distribution.</emphasis>
<collectingCountry id="6FC97642FFF02E3FFE9A269676DEFB28" box="[359,450,1212,1237]" name="Uganda" pageId="14" pageNumber="215">Uganda</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="5FC46559FFF02E3FFF3A26CA7280FB05" box="[199,1436,1248,1273]" pageId="14" pageNumber="215" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="176136D2FFF02E3FFF3A26CA7280FB05" blockId="14.[151,1437,151,1273]" box="[199,1436,1248,1273]" pageId="14" pageNumber="215">
<emphasis id="25AAEAC0FFF02E3FFF3A26CA7652FB04" bold="true" box="[199,334,1248,1273]" pageId="14" pageNumber="215">Etymology.</emphasis>
The species epithet is derived from the Greek, 
<emphasis id="25AAEAC0FFF02E3FFCA126CA748FFB04" box="[860,915,1248,1273]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="215">pilos</emphasis>
(= hair), referring to hairy cilia of the antenna.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
